			<p>An ambitious new Climate Action Plan strengthens the University of Central Florida's status as an innovative leader in &quot;green&quot; operations, classes and research.</p>
<p>The plan, available <a href="http://www.sustainable.ucf.edu/?q=node/115">online</a>, will guide the nation&rsquo;s third-largest university as it works to meet President John Hitt's pledge to become climate neutral by 2050.</p>
<p>With 60,000 faculty, staff and students, UCF faces a more daunting challenge in achieving climate neutrality than most other schools and organizations will encounter. However, UCF's size positions the university to make a more powerful and substantial impact.</p>
<p>&quot;Our dedicated staff members, faculty members, and engaged students have made exceptional strides in reducing the impact of our campus on the environment,&quot; Hitt said. &quot;Working together, we can build on those successes, strengthen our position as a leader in preserving Central Florida's natural beauty, and inspire others to follow our example.&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Taking Action Now: UCF's Climate Action Plan&quot; was submitted to the American College and University Presidents Climate Commitment. Hitt is a founding member of the organization's Leadership Circle.</p>
<p>UCF already has made strides -- and saved $1 million in 2009 -- in several of the five major steps necessary to achieve carbon neutrality: energy conservation, energy efficiency, fuel switching, renewable energy and carbon mitigation.</p>
<p>The university has reduced its energy consumption by 25 percent per square foot in three years and continues to work toward more savings. UCF requires that all new construction be LEED-certified at the silver level or higher by the U.S. Green Building Council. A new thermal energy storage facility chills water for the campus' cooling system at night and stores it for daytime use, adding a projected $700,000 to UCF's annual energy cost savings.</p>
<p>&quot;Green&quot; research at UCF focuses on energy efficiency, renewable and alternative energy, the impacts of climate change and much more. The student-selected unifying theme, &quot;The Environment and Global Climate Change,&quot; has reached several thousand students in a variety of fields of study.</p>
<p>Among the university's longer-term goals, UCF has pledged to reduce its carbon dioxide emissions by at least 17 percent by 2020 and by 42 percent by 2030. UCF will strive to reduce energy consumption to 30 percent below 2005 levels by 2013 and increase its recycling rate to 75 percent by 2020. Also, all new office equipment must meet or exceed Energy Star requirements.</p>
<p>Faculty, staff and students can help by reusing and recycling more materials and reducing their energy consumption by turning off lights and unplugging electronics and phone chargers when not in use.</p>
<p>&quot;A small individual effort by everyone on campus can make a major difference in helping UCF become more energy efficient and achieve our 'green' goals,&quot; said David Norvell, UCF's director of Sustainability and Energy Management.</p>
<p>UCF administrators, students and faculty and staff members have worked together to develop the plan for reducing and mitigating the university's greenhouse gas emissions since President Hitt signed the Climate Commitment pledge in 2007. The plan will be reviewed periodically and updated as necessary.</p>
<p>All are encouraged to view the Climate Action Plan online. To conserve paper, only a limited number of printed copies were made.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF&nbsp;Stands for Opportunity</strong>:&nbsp;The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 3rd largest in the nation with more than 53,000 students. UCF&rsquo;s first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region&rsquo;s economic development. UCF&rsquo;s culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a></p>
		
	
